│ stop({"edit_points": [[13729, 13735, "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1. Understanding the Issue: The SLP vectorizer is incorrectly vectorizing icmp     │
│ instructions with the `samesign` attribute by looking through zext casts and working with the narrower source type (i16) instead of the cast result type (i32). This causes the           │
│ vectorized code to truncate operands to i1, losing the sign information needed for the `samesign` comparison, resulting in poison values where the original code produces concrete        │
│ values.\n\n2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log: The log shows the vectorizer creating a `<4 x i16>` vector from the zext inputs, then truncating to `<4 x i1>`, and performing the icmp on i1        │
│ vectors. The original scalar code operates on i32 values, so the vectorized version should use `<4 x i32>` vectors. The debug output shows the optimization in `CreateInsertElement` that │
│ looks through zext casts is causing this incorrect type selection.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis: In the `gather` function's `CreateInsertElement` lambda (lines 13729-13735), when           │
│ encountering a ZExtInst, the code replaces the cast result with its source operand as an optimization. This assumes it's safe to use the narrower type, but it's incorrect when the cast  │
│ result is used by instructions that depend on the specific bit width (like `samesign` icmp). The optimization doesn't consider that changing the operand type can affect instruction      │
│ semantics.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s): Remove or disable the cast-looking-through optimization in lines 13729-13735 of `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp`. This          │
│ optimization is too aggressive and can change semantics when casts change integer bit widths. The safest approach is to always use the actual cast result type rather than looking        │
│ through to the source operand.\n\n5. Conclusion: By disabling this unsafe optimization, the SLP vectorizer will correctly use the i32 type for the icmp operands, preserving the sign     │
│ information needed for `samesign` comparisons. This will prevent the generation of poison values and ensure the vectorized code is semantically equivalent to the original scalar         │
│ code."})                                                                                                                                                                                  │
